[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 17:8-10. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 17:8-10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And they troubled the people and the rulers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— As the charge was formed in such a manner that their neglecting it might render them obnoxious to the Romans, both the multitude and the magistrates of the city were alarmed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when they heard these things. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They were not willing, however, to proceed to extremities against an inhabitant of the place, merely for harbouring persons who, whatever might be alleged against them, were in a manner strangers to him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "therefore, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when they had taken security of Jason, and the other ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Brethren who were brought before them, that they would behave as good subjects; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they let them go ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Dismissed them for that time. This liberal conduct of the rulers of Thessalonica restrained the malice of the Jews for the present. But ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the brethren ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Fearing some new tumult might arise, thought it prudent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "send Paul and Silas ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And probably Timothy also, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 17:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "away by night to Berea ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— A populous city in the neighbourhood. Luke has not told us what time Paul and his assistants spent at Thessalonica. But there are circumstances mentioned in the apostle’s epistles from which we may infer, that they spent some months in planting a church there; such as that, during his abode at Thessalonica, he received money twice from the Philippians, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 4:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and communicated the spiritual gifts to the brethren in plenty, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and appointed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "προισταμενους",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "presidents, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or rulers, statedly to exercise the ministry among them, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 5:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) having formed them into a regular church; all which implies that he abode a considerable time in this city.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17:1-9 The drift and scope of Paul's preaching and arguing, was to prove that Jesus is the Christ. He must needs suffer for us, because he could not otherwise purchase our redemption for us; and he must needs have risen again, because he could not otherwise apply the redemption to us. We are to preach concerning Jesus that he is Christ; therefore we may hope to be saved by him, and are bound to be ruled by him. The unbelieving Jews were angry, because the apostles preached to the Gentiles, that they might be saved. How strange it is, that men should grudge others the privileges they will not themselves accept! Neither rulers nor people need be troubled at the increase of real Christians, even though turbulent spirits should make religion the pretext for evil designs. Of such let us beware, from such let us withdraw, that we may show a desire to act aright in society, while we claim our right to worship God according to our consciences.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And they troubled the people - They excited the people to commotion and alarm. The rulers feared the tumult that was excited, and the people feared the Romans, when they heard the charge that there were rebels against the government in their city. It does not appear that there was a disposition in the rulers or the people to persecute the apostles; but they were excited and alarmed by the representations of the Jews, and by the mob that they had collected. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7. all do contrary to the decrees of Cæsar, &c.—meaning, probably, nothing but what is specified in the next words.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "saying … there is another king, one Jesus—(See on [2040]Joh 19:12).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "They troubled the people; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " hearing something to have been done against the Roman state, under whom they were, and not knowing what it might come to, or how it might be construed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And the rulers; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for fear of an insurrection and tumult. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
